The term filter parser does allow specifying more than one field without barfing and throwing an exception, resulting in a last one wins scenario.

Sample to reproduce

```
GET /foo/bar/_search
{
  "query": {
    "filtered": {
      "query": {
        "match_all": {}
      },
      "filter": {
        "term": {
          "field2": "bar",
          "field1": "foo"
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

This should throw an exception, once `field2` has been found and is tried to be overwritten.

This seems similar (albeit different) to #12179: there is an issue with "now" and percolator queries: when .percolator documents are filtered in addition to percolation. 

``` json
POST /idx/type/_percolate
{
  "doc": {},
  "filter": {
    "range": {
      "$context.created": {
        "lte": "now"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

for .percolator:

``` json
{
  "query": {
    "filtered": {
      "query": {
        "match_all": []
      }
    }
  },
  "$context": {
    "name": "test",
    "created": "2015-07-10T14:41:54+0000",
  }
}
```

